There is a user who would like to add a field to an enum at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185962/1.   This would require an addition to the model as well inside of Migration.migration_type.  Detection of changes in ENUM is an unhandled case and would need to be addressed here, either by ensuring that all "native" ENUM types are removed from Nova ahead of time or by adding support to detect changes here.  The mechanics of ENUM on MySQL and Postgresql are dramatically different, and on other databases there is no native support, so a CHECK constraint is emitted instead.

If the SQLAlchemy "Enum" type is used (there are three usages of it right now), even if "native" is set to False it still creates a CHECK constraint that would need to be altered, unless that is disabled also; Alembic does not currently detect changes in these either.

Basically the Enum types in models.py either need to be fully converted to a plain CHAR with no constraint of any kind and migrated to that before moving to online schema migrations, or at least support for detection of changes in CHECK constraints and possibly native ENUM types would be needed here.'}, {'account_id': 532, 'date': '2015-06-10 14:07:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Code-Review+1

@Michael, I understand your thoughts on the ENUM, but I believe that code to check and update the CHECK constraints should be separate from this as the online migrations will be the same with our without the change related to ENUMS.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-06-10 14:16:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

commit_message:
Implement online schema migrations

Using the model as a declarative source, generate and schedule schema
changes into expand, migrate and contract phases. This allows some
(and potentially all) of the schema changes to be performed while
services are still running, reducing downtime during deploys.

Updated based on code review to move from iteritems to items based on
recent lists discussions.

Partially-Implements: blueprint online-schema-changes
Change-Id: If666d5162674aaa874ff2c40799f29e23856544d

[{'created': '2015-06-17 15:14:05.000000000', 'message': 'spec: updates for rspec-puppet 2.x and rspec 3.x

This patch aim to update our specs test in order to work with the
rspec-puppet release 2.0.0, in the mean time, we update rspec syntax
in order to be prepared for rspec 3.x move.

In details:
  * Use shared_examples "a Puppet::Error" for puppet::error tests
  * Convert 'should' keyword to 'is_expected.to' (prepare rspec 3.x)
  * Fix spec tests for rspec-puppet 2.0.0
  * Upgrade and pin rspec-puppet from 1.0.1 to 2.0.0
  * Clean Gemfile (remove over-specificication of runtime deps of puppetlabs_spec_helper)
  * Remove un-used puppet-lint (name_containing_dash config)

Change-Id: I1b82e4f6ec0b1bbf52e86c5d127413a26277ae8c
Card: https://trello.com/c/eHXc1Ryd/4-investigate-the-necessary-change-to-be-rspec-puppet-2-0-0-compliant
(cherry picked from commit d7e9fe0e7abecb6963afc3a34c931e3b2e4eaaff)
'}]
commit_message:
spec: updates for rspec-puppet 2.x and rspec 3.x

This patch aim to update our specs test in order to work with the
rspec-puppet release 2.0.0, in the mean time, we update rspec syntax
in order to be prepared for rspec 3.x move.

In details:
  * Use shared_examples "a Puppet::Error" for puppet::error tests
  * Convert 'should' keyword to 'is_expected.to' (prepare rspec 3.x)
  * Fix spec tests for rspec-puppet 2.0.0

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

[{'created': '2015-06-14 05:19:13.000000000', 'message': 'AAP Driver deletes sec grp rule on listener delete

The allowed address pairs driver did not appropriately calculate what ports
should be removed upon a listener deletion.  It does now by removing any
protocol ports of a listener that is in PENDING_DELETE provisioning_status.

Closes-Bug: #1464954
'}]
commit_message:
AAP Driver deletes sec grp rule on listener delete

The allowed address pairs driver did not appropriately calculate what ports
should be removed upon a listener deletion.  It does now by removing any
protocol ports of a listener that is in PENDING_DELETE provisioning_status.

Change-Id: Ice5224d9a9af51a981ee2efad792f037204fba7b
Closes-Bug: #1464954

commit_message:
Do not delete vip port if octavia didn't create it

Octavia should not attempt to delete the vip port if the port was previously
created by another service and its id was passed to Octavia.  It is that
service's responsibility to delete it.

Change-Id: Ia233349e0ade804a2b02145e9ae91b7d3d3e57ce
Closes-Bug: #1464948

[{'created': '2015-06-10 12:59:00.000000000', 'message': "Graceful shutdown WSGI server

Currently, termination of WSGI application immediately stops service and so
interrupts in-progress request. This could cause problem when do upgrading.

Following related things were done:
1. Removed signal handler for SIGINT to allow instantaneous shutdown.
2. Call launcher.stop() was moved from _child_wait_for_exit_or_signal method
to SIGTERM signal handler and pipe_watcher method because service must not be
stopped for example if SIGHUP comes.
3. Added stop server operation before sending TERM signal to children
processes to close listening socket in master process. Because if socket in
master process is opened, user could successfully connects to API server but
without receiving response.
4. On children side before calling _exit() added call launcher.wait() to allow
gracefully shutdown on SIGTERM.
5. Removed service.wait() from Services.stop() to make it not-blocking call.
6. Removed stop-start operations from Services.restart method because of two
reasons:
  - why stop/start service if we have reset() service's method;
  - to allow graceful shutdown implementation of service.stop() must contain
    closing listening server socket. And there is no possibility to open new
    socket and bind it with current address/port in service.start method if it
    was closed.

DocImpact: graceful termination of process can be done by sending SIGTERM
signal to parent WSGI process. Graceful termination is not instantaneous.
To force instantaneous termination SIGINT signal must be sent.

Change-Id: If25f9565d832d1c36642ec3b1921563ef02890aa
Closes-bug: #1382390
Co-Author: Tiantian Gao <gtt116@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Graceful shutdown WSGI/RPC server

Currently, termination of WSGI application or RPC server immediately stops
service and so interrupts in-progress request.

Graceful handler for SIGTERM signal was added.
SIGINT signal handler was removed to allow instantaneous termination of
service.

DocImpact: graceful termination of process can be done by sending SIGTERM
signal to parent WSGI process. Graceful termination is not instantaneous.
To force instantaneous termination SIGINT signal must be sent.

Change-Id: If25f9565d832d1c36642ec3b1921563ef02890aa
Closes-bug: #1382390
Co-Author: Tiantian Gao <gtt116@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Added 'pool name' and 'flavor name' to response

'pool name and flavor name were being deleted from the response. I
'eliminated the pop() function thas was causing this.

This change is needed because in order to create an instance of pool
or a flavor, the 'name' attribute is required.

Change-Id: I36445838f532e9f282a4f839a0f583257c1f13d9
Closes-Bug: #1463474

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Ib9106f86b1a04825c24bb2be284c17590f941d3c

commit_message:
libvirt: safe_decode xml for i18n logging

The xml argument passed to _create_domain can be a utf-8 encoded string
which causes a UnicodeDecodeError when it is substituted into the _LE
unicode translated message. Safely decoding the xml argument before
attempting to substitute it into the error message avoids the
UnicodeDecodeError.

(cherry picked from commit 96a2283c1a07f0298c57f57d8c4112c1c33b6128)

Conflicts:

	nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

Closes-Bug: #1453274
Change-Id: I4cf1836f4ca9097f7c6d98c5212a14d24111fe67

commit_message:
Juno_initial migration

Havana was deprecated with the kilo release, and icehouse will be
deprecated with the liberty release, so havana_inital migration should be
removed and replaced with juno_initial.

Closes-bug: #1461103

commit_message:
Shotgun: fixed password prompt when wrong ssh key

When shotgun tries to connect to a remote node with wrong
ssh key it falls into password dialog and prevents diagnostic
snapshot to be gathered. It is possible when, for example,
node is booted into bootstrap OS while nailgun thinks all
nodes are booted into target OS.

Change-Id: I7055ee1ac8d725c5f342f3255ef53018dd9d4022
Closes-Bug: #1466045

commit_message:
Replace oslo incubator code with i18n

This commit is part of a series of commits to replace our oslo incubator
code with official oslo packages found on PyPI. The modules replaced in
this commit were either found in i18n, were dependencies of other replaced
modules, or just not used anymore.

Change-Id: I3f5276331f37b6824a25255b692d79bdb2a4c830
Partial-Bug: 1463967

commit_message:
Submit new project puppet-openstack-cookiecutter

During last summit, it was decided during the puppet-openstack design
session that the community will provide an easy way for new project to
bootstrap their puppet module with a 'compliant' design.

A cookiecutter template was created[1], after mentioning it on the
list[2] and during the weekly meeting[3] it is a go from the community that
this project should be on stackforge so everyone can contribute to it
and so it is on the scope it belongs.

[1] https://github.com/enovance/puppet-openstack-cookiecutter
[2]
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/064608.html
[3]
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/puppet_openstack/2015/puppet_openstack.2015-06-02-15.00.html

Change-Id: I18abf0f35f2787b9252a02a9293a669ab1389319

Add some accessor methods to CloudConfig

There are some questions that people might want to ask without
necessarily digging in to the underlying dict (this came up when
noodling on openstacksdk factory functions.

commit_message:
Handle Interrupt in conductor service

Currently, conductor service doesn't handle interrupts, so it will show
lots of call trace if gets KeyboardInterrupt.

This patch improves this by puting in service.launcher, which already has
better interrupts handling.

Closes-Bug: #1465472
Change-Id: I6a6948c9942cc7c84fcf4ce22b029e7b6727c84e

commit_message:
Remove usage of openstack.common._i18n module

Module openstack.common._i18n was removed from Horizon.
So we need to remove usages of this module to fix
manila-ui.
Also remove openstack-common.conf because
oslo-incubator code is not used anymore in Horizon.

Change-Id: I3183f1dff1fecea479be7f3caf4a7906d4947f03
Closes-Bug: #1466086

commit_message:
tests: glusterfs: Remove online snapshot related tests

Since all of the online snapshot handling code moved to remotefs.py
and test_remotefs.py (see Needed By patch) has enough tests for the same,
it time to remove these tests from test_glusterfs.py which was (probably)
forgotten to be removed in the past, when things were moved to
remotefs.py

Related Patch: Ifa2836a87271d465af61c4ae4b2018cde0698924
Change-Id: I915785842a6143512d3bdabe203ccfcb5110773b

commit_message:
Remove nova_proxy_admin_user from trove guest

The nova_proxy_admin_user isn't required on the guest agent, and can
be removed. This is used to look up the admin context, but doing this
is unnecessary since the user context is what should be passed to the
conductor. For heartbeats, a context is not needed and just passing an
empty dict should suffice.

Change-Id: Ic41abe58fcf4b7022360b59dad0bc3af1205b9ba
Closes-bug: 1339349
Co-authored-by: Nikhil Manchanda <SlickNik@gmail.com>
Co-authored-by: Amrith Kumar <amrith@tesora.com>

Sergey, this is actually not an update to template, it's base for all spec commits that creates toctree for specs for 7.0. It just can't be empty, thus Sean copied template there. It will be deleted in the first commit to land based on this one."}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-06-17 08:39:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Look at PS1 and PS2 - Sphinx gets very angry when you put in a TOC entry and there are no files in the path that you specified, and it also gets very angry when you create an empty file. 

We do the same thing in Neutron for neutron-specs - see

https://github.com/openstack/neutron-specs/blob/master/specs/liberty/dummy.rst

https://github.com/openstack/neutron-specs/blob/master/specs/liberty/example.rst'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-06-17 14:35:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180181/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192662/

Which means we're going to end up with a merge conflict when one finally merges, and everyone else is going to have to resolve."}, {'account_id': 6677, 'date': '2015-06-17 15:05:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 6677, 'date': '2015-06-17 15:14:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Revert "Run full tempest on centos7"

This reverts commit e4007efd50fcc1f7c8ea05a85ec4df5fb79d3d08.

Centos7 + nova-network is unstable when running tempest in parallel.
Revert to the smoke-tests while we sort this out.

Change-Id: Ib61fd3fdcbaa41640f5af59152656f6f448638bd

commit_message:
Run requirements update entrypoint from a venv

The requirements update.py script is growing its own dependencies so
we need to install it into a virtualenv and run it from there. Also,
go ahead and switch to invoking its entrypoint since it'll be
installed for us now. Also run the generate-constraints entrypoint
from a virtualenv similarly.

Change-Id: I16e967356d5c56f1474ee661b954b3db11a608cb

commit_message:
Change tag ACLs for library projects to library-release team

As part of the plan to move release tagging permissions to a core group
managed under the release management team [1], update the ACLs files to
give permissions so a new library-release team instead of the existing
core or release teams. When the new team is created, the "Release
Managers" group and a small number of volunteers will be added to it.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066346.html

Change-Id: I9d1568fa688c08b658444b33df0408907d0b3fa6

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-03 06:10:10.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure netfilter is enabled for bridges

Since security-groups use iptables rules on Linux bridges, we need to
ensure that netfilter is enabled for bridges.  Unfortunately, there
seems to be a long history of distributions having differing defaults
for this, best described in [1].

It seems at the moment everyone has to discover this for themselves;
packstack found it in Ia8c86dcb31810a8d6b133a161388604fde9bead4, then
fuel found the same thing in I8582c24706c3a7253e00569eef275f116d765bca
and then finally someone else hit it and put it into documentation
with I4ed3cec03a1b3a7d56dfe18394154ec1b2db6791.  I just spent a long
time figuring it out too when deploying with devstack.

This change ensures that the required proc settings for bridge
filtering are set and halts the agent if not.  It will be up to the
user to figure out how to enable these settings, but this avoids being
able to continue on with security groups being silently broken.

Test-cases are updated to check the failure case.

Note this is proposed as an alternative to
Idf17bfc1a838cbdee90aeced594247360fcf55b4.  There was concern in that
change that neutron was changing the state of the bridge settings.

[1] http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf

Change-Id: I8b49298d27a75a864c0066896cbd3d3095982f6e

commit_message:
Ensure netfilter is enabled for bridges

Since security-groups use iptables rules on Linux bridges, we need to
ensure that netfilter is enabled for bridges.  Unfortunately, there
seems to be a long history of distributions having differing defaults
for this, best described in [1].

It seems at the moment everyone has to discover this for themselves;
packstack found it in Ia8c86dcb31810a8d6b133a161388604fde9bead4, then
fuel found the same thing in I8582c24706c3a7253e00569eef275f116d765bca
and then finally someone else hit it and put it into documentation
with I4ed3cec03a1b3a7d56dfe18394154ec1b2db6791.  I just spent a long
time figuring it out too when deploying with devstack.

This change ensures that the required proc settings for bridge
filtering are set and halts the agent if not.  It will be up to the
user to figure out how to enable these settings, but this avoids being
able to continue on with security groups being silently broken.

Test-cases are updated to check the failure case.

Note this is proposed as an alternative to
If2d316eb8c422dc1e4f34b17a50b93dd72993a99 which would make neutron
turn on these settings.  There was concern in that change that neutron
was changing too much state.

[1] http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf

Change-Id: I8b49298d27a75a864c0066896cbd3d3095982f6e

@Ian - true, IP_VERSION ended up getting merged (I848abf18e00e2a869697c5ef6366bc567dde448a) with IP_VERSION just controlling the creation of tenant data networks, since it was agreed the patch was too large to also re-configure the IP stack of all the services to listen on IPv4 and IPv6. 

I'm OK with defining a new variable and documenting it to just have all the services listen on both IPv4 and IPv6 - it'd probably be a boolean to make things easier. 

Thanks for your patience, I only know enough shell script to blow my feet off, so I'll probably make some stupid patches that you'll cringe at."}, {'account_id': 10257, 'date': '2015-04-30 08:37:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Thanks @Sean for letting me know about this patch.

However, there is a small difference between this patch and the one i have submitted [1].
What i was planning to do in patch [1], was to have an IPv6 "only" based setup (i.e., an environment where the host does not have any IPv4 address).
In fact, my plan was to extend it to a multi-node IPv6 "only" setup. BTW, I have a working IPv6 only multi-node setup (using VLANs) at my place. 

In the current patch we are binding the services to '::' which makes it reachable both on IPv4 as well as IPv6 addresses. 
I'm interested to know, if you have plans to extend the current patch to the use-case I have mentioned. 

I'll be happy to review your patch or collaborate with you on this patch to enhance devstack for IPv6 support :-)
Please let me know your thoughts.

[1] - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176898/'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-06-16 17:43:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I just posted https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192329/ as well to support having either an IPv4 or IPv6 control plane for devstack services, it was just enough different from this that I didn't want to just over-write this one."}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-06-17 15:03:15.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

@Brian - sounds good, let's put all our energy into your review"}]

commit_message:
Add support for IP_VERSION in other services

This change adds support for the IP_VERSION config flag in DevStack, and
configures services to listen on IPv6 addresses.

This commit is a partial cherry-pick of patch set #1 of
I848abf18e00e2a869697c5ef6366bc567dde448a

Co-Authored-By: Baodong Li <baoli@cisco.com>

Change-Id: I1043f6a216b2b7aa33f450d4af2e536d0309bbb7

I like the idea, but it needs some refinement.

The design so far is that admins define the semantics of types and properties, and they are interpreted by consumers.  This works only if the consumers are taught the relevant semantics by the admins.

I agree with the need to focus on real use cases.  So I have one to contribute.  Consider the policy catalog given in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Heat/PolicyExtension and think about what a holistic scheduler needs in order to implement such a combination of policies.

To make a holistic scheduler that includes networking constraints, the scheduler needs to be able to derive the relevant consequences from the data available from this API.  That includes understanding the semantics of the types and properties.

I do not understand the exclusion of VLANs.  Please work an end-to-end example in which the hosts do no VLAN tagging or processing, some switches introduce and remove VLAN tagging.'}, {'account_id': 333, 'date': '2014-06-20 05:19:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

(2 comments)

I have a few comments in-line, and here I will elaborate on my earlier request to work a VLAN example.  My concern is driven by line 199, which says that VLANs are not modeled.  It seems to me that excluding VLANs makes it impossible to draw useful conclusions about what can communicate with what.

Consider the following example.  There are six network nodes: four compute nodes and two switches, arranged like a hydrazine molecule.  Compute nodes C11 and C12 are each linked to switch S1, which is also linked to switch S2, which is also linked to compute nodes C21 and C22.  Switch S1 push/pops VLAN tag V1 on traffic with C11, tag V2 on traffic with C12; switch S2 push/pops VLAN tag V1 on traffic with C21, tag V2 on traffic with C22.  Thus, C11 and C21 can communicate, and C12 and C22 can communicate, the but C11 can NOT communicate with C22 and C12 can NOT communicate with C21.  If the model ignores the VLAN tagging then a consumer of such a model will incorrectly deduce that C11 can communicate with C22, and so on.

In a related vein: do you intend to model middleboxes that do things like firewalls?  If so then connectivity is not only a matter of host address, it is also a question of protocol and port and possibly even data content.'}, {'account_id': 333, 'date': '2014-07-09 04:32:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

At this point, the deduction could be inefficient. But we can optimize it later for common use case.

commit_message:
physical-network-topology extension spec

This spec describes extension that manages physical network topology.
This allows plugin/mechanism driver to easily utilize the information
of underlying network topology for better resource usage.

Change-Id: I7173d4dd0fc1de8bfebb80d824d63e3eb7ff027e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-22 13:39:56.000000000', 'message': 'mirror/centos: fail on broken/missing package(s)

Apparently yumdownloader does not raise an error if some packages are
missing or broken (dependencies can not be satisfied). As a result some
packages have silently disappered from the mirror (kmod-openvswitch) and
others have been broken (sheepdog).

Patch yumdownloader so it bails out if some packages are missing or have
broken dependencies. As a side effect yumdownloader raises an error if
some of the packages being downloaded conflict (like kernel-headers vs
kernel-headers-lt), so modify the mirroring code to detect and handle
the conflicting packages.

Closes-Bug: #1457382
Related-Bug: #1456459
Change-Id: I404b662cd3b54ee9d058692bb30177b985871b16
'}, {'created': '2015-05-23 19:20:50.000000000', 'message': 'mirror/centos: fail on broken/missing package(s)

Apparently yumdownloader does not raise an error if some packages are
missing or broken (dependencies can not be satisfied). As a result some
packages have silently disappered from the mirror (kmod-openvswitch) and
others have been broken (sheepdog).

Patch yumdownloader so it bails out if some packages are missing or have
broken dependencies. As a side effect yumdownloader raises an error if
some of the packages being downloaded conflict (like kernel-headers vs
kernel-headers-lt), so modify the mirroring code to detect and handle
the conflicting packages.

More strict dependencies check yield some unexpected issues. In
particular a few 32 bit packages are broken due to the upgraded base
packages from Fuel repo being x86_64 only. In particular, 32 bit dmraid
package is broken due to device-mapper-libs:

Package: device-mapper-libs-1.02.79-8.el6.i686 (base)
    Requires: device-mapper = 1.02.79-8.el6
    Available: device-mapper-1.02.79-8.el6.x86_64 (base)
        device-mapper = 1.02.79-8.el6
    Installing: device-mapper-1.02.90-2.mira1.x86_64 (fuel)
        device-mapper = 1.02.90-2.mira1

To solve the problem configure yum to exclude most of i686 packages.
The configuration appeared to be a bit cumbersome since *some* i686
packages are required. In particular syslinux package requires
syslinux-nonlinux (binaries which run in syslinux environment before
booting the OS) which is formally an i686 package.

Closes-Bug: #1457382
Related-Bug: #1456459
Merge-After: https://review.fuel-infra.org/6912
Merge-After: https://review.fuel-infra.org/6909
Change-Id: I404b662cd3b54ee9d058692bb30177b985871b16

the conflicting packages.

particular a few 32 bit packages are broken due to the upgraded base

package is broken due to device-mapper-libs:

To solve the problem configure yum to exclude most of i686 packages.
The configuration appeared to be a bit cumbersome since *some* i686
packages are required. In particular syslinux package requires
syslinux-nonlinux (binaries which run in syslinux environment before
booting the OS) which is formally an i686 package.

commit_message:
mirror/centos: fail on broken/missing package(s)

Apparently yumdownloader does not raise an error if some packages are
missing or broken (dependencies can not be satisfied). As a result some
packages have silently disappered from the mirror (kmod-openvswitch) and
others have been broken (sheepdog).

Patch yumdownloader so it bails out if some packages are missing or have
broken dependencies. As a side effect yumdownloader raises an error if
some of the packages being downloaded conflict (like kernel-headers vs
kernel-headers-lt), so modify the mirroring code to detect and handle
the conflicting packages.

More strict dependencies check yield some unexpected issues. In
particular a few 32 bit packages are broken due to the upgraded base
packages from Fuel repo being x86_64 only. In particular, 32 bit dmraid
package is broken due to device-mapper-libs:

Package: device-mapper-libs-1.02.79-8.el6.i686 (base)
    Requires: device-mapper = 1.02.79-8.el6
    Available: device-mapper-1.02.79-8.el6.x86_64 (base)
        device-mapper = 1.02.79-8.el6
    Installing: device-mapper-1.02.90-2.mira1.x86_64 (fuel)
        device-mapper = 1.02.90-2.mira1

To solve the problem configure yum to exclude most of i686 packages.
The configuration appeared to be a bit cumbersome since *some* i686
packages are required. In particular syslinux package requires
syslinux-nonlinux (binaries which run in syslinux environment before
booting the OS) which is formally an i686 package.

Closes-Bug: #1457382
Related-Bug: #1456459
Change-Id: I404b662cd3b54ee9d058692bb30177b985871b16

commit_message:
Support RedHat yum installation

bifrost does not support RedHat rpm installation, in this patch,
added RedHat rpms list, and replace 'apt' Ubuntu command to ansible
pkg_mgr var to support both Ubuntu and RedHat.

And remove the duplication testing packages installation section.

Closes-bug: 1456896
Change-Id: I58d627d3deb4a8a2712f242429e93b8ded9cfb76

Lets not add a link to Admin Guide here:

http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/content/section_telemetry-supported-dbs.html

As, this link  includes database back ends supported for only Ceilometer. For example, Keystone does not support ElasticSearch.

Also, in the admin guide, when it says multiple database back ends can be configured, "multiple" means any combination of database back ends from the list.

Lets rephrase this statement to:

"Majority of OpenStack services supports MySQL and PostgreSQL database back ends. Some OpenStack services also supports ElasticSearch, MongoDB, HBase, and DB2."

Please feel free to suggest rephrasing this statement.

Cheers

commit_message:
[security-guide]Change to generalized term database.

Openstack support multiple databases,only few were mentioned.
Included a generalized term of database while maintaining the
integrity of context.

solving a small typing error in preface also.

Change-Id: I63856a114698b5ac19b3ecf594ea6b984032ed90
Closes-Bug: #1464546

commit_message:
CLI support for message CRUD operations

This patch extends the queues operation supported by the CLI.

Features added:
- List the messages
- Post a message
- Get one or set of messages
- Delete one or set of messages

Some examples:
    $ openstack message list --queue_name test_queue
    $ openstack message post --queue_name test_queue --ttl 3600 \
        --body '{"name":"user1", "password":"pass"}'
    $ openstack message get --queue_name test_queue \
        778899 889900 990011
    $ openstack message delete --queue_name test_queue \
        778899 889900 990011

Change-Id: I5ebd153f32704e616fa78d388bf3d50f36c287fa
Partially-Implements: blueprint cli

commit_message:
Rename volume to block_store

In line with other renamings we've made, the volume service is really
the "block store service". It's still called volume in the service
catalog, which is why it was originally named that, but block storage is
how it exists in projects.yaml as well as how it's actuall referred to.

Change-Id: Ic97dfc83561844dd3dcbd569b272f8f1a853f436

commit_message:
CLI support for claim CRUD operations

This patch extends the queues operation supported by the CLI.

Features added:
- Create claim
- Query claim
- Update claim
- Release claim

Some examples:
    $ openstack claim create --queue_name test_queue --ttl 3600 \
        --grace 120
    $ openstack claim query --queue_name test_queue 7788990
    $ openstack claim update --queue_name test_queue --ttl 720 \
        7788990
    $ openstack claim release --queue_name test_queue 7788990

Change-Id: I610b1b236376e6be19014717dbe926d8a749198d
Partially-Implements: blueprint cli

commit_message:
Add a non-voting check-tempest-dsvm-neutron job

This job will be used to test the feature branch (feature/pecan) in
Neutron while we stabilize the new WSGI layer.

Change-Id: If5cb17d697fd326dca8f616a4d5fcc3d6943ccfd
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

Performing low-level modification of global system config at runtime is something that we generally try to avoid.  While sysctl is being invoked at runtime in existing code, that usage is limited to namespaces and specific devices rather than global settings.  Global settings are typically managed by a system administrator or deployment software so I'm not sure that Neutron should be doing it automatically.

The way I've seen this kind of issue handled in the past has been checking the state of the underlying system on startup and failing agent startup if an incompatible state is detected.  Sanity checks are one way of encapsulating such checks:

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/cmd/sanity/checks.py"}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:06:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Ah ok Ian, that makes sense.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:10:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Maru, while I generally agree, and I have directed ian to sanity checks other times, this issue is very subtle, and it's going to look like everything is ok all the time (no error logs, nothing...)

Just iptables security groups don't work, and people gets frustrated, either in devstack or distros.

I guess, another approach could be running the sanity checks before starting any other agent, in devstack and distros.

Anyway, the agent does all sort of system settings manipulations (device creation, iptables, ipsets..., why sysctl is different from that?, we're not modifying config files, for example).

In this case, something like this would have saved me hours of debugging or helping people debug their systems. :)"}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:13:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

btw, comparing to other checks:

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/cmd/sanity/checks.py

Here we're not checking a tool version, or the parameters supported by a tool. We're just modifying the network node kernel parameters so iptables netfilter hooks as are called as expected in the bridges."}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:29:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

As per discussion in #openstack-neutron, the fact that the config issue being addressed is distro-specific suggests that it should be detected in the code but remedied by deployment tools.  Neutron should not have to be doing distro-specific fixup at runtime, since that's a slippery slope to unnecessary complexity."}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:37:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: -Code-Review

Yes, as @maru says, that's the outcome of the irc discussion. Since it's a distro-specific deviation of the kernel standard settings, we may leave that to the deployment tools.

I'd suggest moving this into a sanity check, ongoing example here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186782/

May be other useful steps:

1)  Setting this in devstack for EL systems, 

2) Running sanity checks in devstack to make sure everything else is right..."}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-29 17:12:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-06-01 05:33:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

> Neutron should not have to be doing distro-specific fixup at runtime, since that's a slippery slope to unnecessary complexity.

I think in this case neutron has already fallen head-first down the slippery slope.  It's just neutron didn't notice because all the wasted time and complexity on this is an externality.

This is not really distro specific or platform specific or a work-around.  If you asked for the OVSHybridIptablesFirewallDriver you have implicitly asked for these settings turned be turned on.  They are one-and-the-same; it is not optional or discresionary and you can not continue with it turned off.  OVSHybridIptablesFirewallDriver == netfilter on bridges    

Perhaps this distinction is unclear because the existing documentation around these settings gives no rationale and does not make this relationship clear.  I have proposed I42c6a0219d960b682bb4a39727c87151bc3ef1a8 to help clarify the situation in conjunction with this.

We could make this error out.  At least that avoids the "silently broken" bit.  But why do we hate our users so much that we don't just turn it on for them, and instead make them go and rearchitecture their deployment method?  Again, they have no option but to turn this on, or not use the hybrid driver.

I don't see what good those asynchronous sanity checks really are.  Somebody could go and fix on a live system and pass the sanity checks, but after a reboot it would be back to silently broken.  Silent runtime failure is just a horrible experience we should avoid.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-01 10:04:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-01 12:33:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

I want to avoid tuning global kernel params at runtime as well. I am concerned about the silent failure mode too. I would support a startup check that bails out if the filter isn't enabled."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-03 11:57:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Kevin, @Maru, would you be ok if the tweak is applied to those devices that openstack manages only, leaving global state intact?'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:06:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@IHar -- bridge firewalling is a global thing; it's either on or off.  see [1]

[1] http://git.kernel.org/cgit/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git/tree/net/bridge/br_netfilter.c"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:16:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@Ian, thanks for the answer. That's unfortunate.

To help deployers, we could ship a file to put into /etc/sysctl.d/ and install it using setuptools."}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:19:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@ianw is correct, I made a comment about shipping the sysctl.d file in the neutron agents package, that would solve the issue from the distro/packaging side.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:22:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@ihar, nope, I was checking comments, and it seems I only thought about using sysctl.d but never commented, ajo-- ! ;/'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:31:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

I'm not sure that helps that much because the module may not be loaded during boot.  Its all a PITA any way it is done :)"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:32:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@Miguel, note that packagers would still need to make sure we reload sysctl conf files (sysctl --system) before we start a newly installed agent, otherwise the service may fail until the next system reboot. I guess in RPM world it's done using %post rules in .spec file."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-03 12:33:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@Ian, I would expect sysctl.d files to apply on module load, not just initial system boot. Isn't it the case?"}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-06-03 20:59:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Ihar - if you see [1] I think the only conclusion you can draw is "it's unclear"

Anyway, shipping a file like that really *is* modifying too much global state for my liking.  Seeing as it's only necessary for one driver, and you might not even want that driver, we shouldn't be stuffing extra settings files around 

In short, I think it's fine to do as this patch does as say "enabling OVS hybrid enables bridge+netfilter".  It's idempotent (if it's already set, setting it again doesn't hurt) and it does the right thing always.

If we can't agree on that, we should at *least* bail out as per I8b49298d27a75a864c0066896cbd3d3095982f6e (I'm working on your comments there)

[1] http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-06-17 12:41:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1

I'm catching up on this, but I'm tending to agree with Ian here and I'm not understanding why we're not moving forward with this patch."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-06-17 13:17:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2

After discussion with Sean, Ian and Ihar, I think we should move forward with this. It's pointless to punt this type of thing to installers when the simple fact is we're broken without as is currently implemented."}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-06-17 13:26:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1

I re+1 , since I agree that as an idempotent system setting it's not going to do any harm to set it, and then deployers don't need to know obscure things about neutron agents."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-17 13:26:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-07 05:29:05.000000000', 'message': "Ensure netfilter is enabled for bridges

Since security-groups use iptables rules on Linux bridges, we need to
ensure that netfilter is enabled for bridges.  Unfortunately, there
seems to be a long history of distributions having differing defaults
for this, best described in [1].

It seems at the moment everyone has to discover this for themselves;
packstack found it in Ia8c86dcb31810a8d6b133a161388604fde9bead4, then
fuel found the same thing in I8582c24706c3a7253e00569eef275f116d765bca
and then finally someone else hit it and put it into documentation
with I4ed3cec03a1b3a7d56dfe18394154ec1b2db6791.  I just spent a long
time figuring it out too when deploying with devstack.

Rather than having yet another fix in devstack, I don't see why
neutron shouldn't be ensuring the setting is correct when it starts up
-- without these settings enabled, security-groups are silently
broken.  This does that, and modifies test-cases to check we make the
calls.

[1] http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf

Change-Id: If2d316eb8c422dc1e4f34b17a50b93dd72993a99
"}, {'created': '2015-05-08 01:14:26.000000000', 'message': "Ensure netfilter is enabled for bridges

commit_message:
Ensure netfilter is enabled for bridges

Since security-groups use iptables rules on Linux bridges, we need to
ensure that netfilter is enabled for bridges.  Unfortunately, there
seems to be a long history of distributions having differing defaults
for this, best described in [1].

It seems at the moment everyone has to discover this for themselves;
packstack found it in Ia8c86dcb31810a8d6b133a161388604fde9bead4, then
fuel found the same thing in I8582c24706c3a7253e00569eef275f116d765bca
and then finally someone else hit it and put it into documentation
with I4ed3cec03a1b3a7d56dfe18394154ec1b2db6791.  I just spent a long
time figuring it out too when deploying with devstack.

Rather than having yet another fix in devstack, I don't see why
neutron shouldn't be ensuring the setting is correct when it starts up
-- without these settings enabled, security-groups are silently
broken.  This does that, and modifies test-cases to check we make the
calls.

[1] http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf

Change-Id: If2d316eb8c422dc1e4f34b17a50b93dd72993a99

commit_message:
Configurable vlan_id's for isolated networks

This patch adds parameters to configure the various
vlan IDs to all of the bond-with-vlans and single-nic-vlans
network config templates.

Change-Id: Ia6196735927777b73879e8086568f8a435597c6c

commit_message:
NPIV Port login-logout changes

This change includes mapping the fabric to the management
partition so that NPIV WWPNs are logged in to the FC physical
fabric. This will allow the WWPNs to be properly zoned via
cinder zone manager, as well as can be made available to the
cinder storage host.
Once the mapping is done and zones are created, later on these
mappings are removed from the management partition (logout) so
that they can be remapped to the client VM.
Different Fabric states are maintained in the instance system
metadata for each state during the entire lifecycle.
Three supported states:
'unmapped': Initial fabric state with no mapping.
'mgmt_mapped': Fabric is mapped to the management partition.
'inst_mapped': Fabric is mapped to the actual client VM instance.

Change-Id: Ic2f564ebd182024a11947e9b06ba297fe3394495

commit_message:
[Ceilometer] Improve create_meter function

Current patchset adds a function create_samples that creates
amount of samples and improve create_meter_get_stats_scenario to
creating amount of samples instead of one for every meter.
It allows to check performance of get_stats function.

Change-Id: I871bdfcb2fad3980bb0f21ad5407685db7783351

commit_message:
Remove unused static (binary) files from manifest tree

due http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/064287.html
any binary files are stored in the files/ hierarchy
and will be packaged while ISO creates.

Change-Id: I61740aa35dc13513e5a365a3363f357035f29a80

commit_message:
Not add datasource if configured datasource is disabled

Synchronizer will try to add datasource if it's configured but
not active. It should not do this if the datasource is disabled
because disabled datasource was added before but expected to
be inactive.
Also mask passowrds in ds config.

Closes-Bug: #1452097
Change-Id: I8c8dbb8d8c7f6d7554c2f66728fb080f089f89c9

commit_message:
Also install alembic_migration folder

In Debian, doing "python setup.py install" fails to install the
alembic migration folder. This patch, which we currently carry
in the debian/patches folder, fixes it. Please allow it to reach
upstream, as it simplifies a lot our package maintainer's life if
it is there.

Change-Id: I640aa91c9c917483e6656f550c191c4d58636070

commit_message:
Reduce neutron API timeout to 10 seconds

If the neutron server is down, 120 seconds is far too long to wait for
puppet to fail. This patch reduces the timeout to 10 seconds because if
the neutron server is flaky, but not down, 10 seconds is a reasonable
amount of time to retry connecting.

commit_message:
Eventlet service fixed

eventlet_service is designed to test ProcessLauncher in pair with
eventlet server. As long as ProcessLauncher uses cfg.CONF.config_file
option we need to register it. This option can be register with
cfg.CONF() call.

Change-Id: I8c3a557f66d8f1db8733d04dd7793425188ee29c

commit_message:
Install iptables-services dependency on Fedora

This patch installs the iptables-services package on Fedora. Without
this dependency the systemd files to start/stop/enable iptables
will not be present.

Change-Id: I822344a7ce394e6054dafe1aa5c34dad7c70c252
Closes-Bug: #1465250

[{'created': '2015-06-16 16:05:33.000000000', 'message': 'Remove raise Timeout::Error from ntp_available

The ntp_available function should not raise a Timeout::Error here as
it should just return false so that the next server should be checked.
This update addresses the case where a Timeout::Error is being raised
rather than having all servers checked before erroring with a
Puppet::Error if no servers answer.

Change-Id: Ibf2ebb80c04e4314f01b9a45e6a2169e1cde7fbf
Closes-Bug: 1465598
'}]
commit_message:
Remove raise Timeout::Error from ntp_available

The ntp_available function should not raise a Timeout::Error here as
it should just return false so that the next server should be checked.
This update addresses the case where a Timeout::Error is being raised
rather than having all servers checked before erroring with a
Puppet::Error if no servers answer.

Change-Id: Ibf2ebb80c04e4314f01b9a45e6a2169e1cde7fbf
Closes-Bug: 1465598

commit_message:
spec: updates for rspec-puppet 2.x and rspec 3.x

This patch aim to update our specs test in order to work with the new
rspec-puppet release 2.0.0, in the mean time, we update rspec syntax
in order to be prepared for rspec 3.x move.

In details:

  * Use shared_examples "a Puppet::Error" for puppet::error tests
  * Convert 'should' keyword to 'is_expected.to' (prepare rspec 3.x)
  * Fix spec tests for rspec-puppet 2.0.0
  * Upgrade and pin rspec-puppet from 1.0.1 to 2.0.0
  * Clean Gemfile (remove over-specificication of runtime deps of puppetlabs_spec_helper)

Conflicts:
	Gemfile
	spec/classes/ceilometer_db_postgresql_spec.rb
	spec/classes/ceilometer_db_spec.rb

Change-Id: Ieaff6bc8bdd8548648ff5e76b212d4df382fa8a3
Card: https://trello.com/c/eHXc1Ryd/4-investigate-the-necessary-change-to-be-rspec-puppet-2-0-0-compliant
(cherry picked from commit 55b7aad8cf0c902cd1469da8547f24e856b06de4)

commit_message:
Add oslo.policy namespace

As we have used oslo.policy, so we need to add that in
namespace, as oslo.policy has many settings. This followed
other projects genconfig ways.

Partially-implements: blueprint policy-enforce
Change-Id: I83cce25427b65aad6d26f4ea2d6a48170233a4f3

On Windows Threshold, a new WMI class was introduced, targeting
VM serial ports.

For this reason, attempting to retrieve serial port connections
fails on Windows Threshold.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an extra check and using the
right WMI class in order to retrieve VM serial ports.

Closes-Bug: #1466056

Change-Id: Ibaf6ac2e77b6324538c6f3dbaacab2a5f065b4ce
(cherry picked from commit 3518220e6313201d5582f14ad73c734453bbe23a)
'}]
commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fix serial port issue on Windows Threshold

On Windows Threshold, a new WMI class was introduced, targeting
VM serial ports.

For this reason, attempting to retrieve serial port connections
fails on Windows Threshold.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an extra check and using the
right WMI class in order to retrieve VM serial ports.

Closes-Bug: #1466056

Change-Id: Ibaf6ac2e77b6324538c6f3dbaacab2a5f065b4ce
(cherry picked from commit 3518220e6313201d5582f14ad73c734453bbe23a)

commit_message:
Added Lint job (nonvoting) to horizon-check

This patch switches horizon from using an explicitly declared
npm run job, to using the javascript-jobs template. It also
adds the `npm run lint` job to the check queue.

Change-Id: I122a7fba04dfba0e036be9b6ccd52d60c1cc36a9
Depends-on: I2c92a7596a8faee28de582493bdf72425deac8cc

Update bifrost job settings

Extending the bifrost job timeout since it is occasionally hitting
the timeout as well as adding preservation of logs.

Change-Id: I715e237853619fbd57d93bf3c7df663998c7a494

commit_message:
Add uname -a to net-info macro

Having the kernel and hostname in the console output is very helpful,
as devstack-gate only outputs this during the setup phase, which is
redirected to a log file ... but if the job fails and the logs aren't
copied, you can't figure this out.

Change-Id: I88630619d03cd35c815953e67f40d5e8b148af3c

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-05 01:37:36.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure netfilter enabled for bridges with OVS Hybrid

The OVS Hybrid driver implements security groups by using netfilter on
an intermediate Linux bridge.  Unfortunately distributions differ on
the default status of this (Ubuntu has it on, Red Hat off, at least).

Neutron is unwilling to set this up itself
(If2d316eb8c422dc1e4f34b17a50b93dd72993a99) but I have a review out to
detect this situation and halt the agent
(I8b49298d27a75a864c0066896cbd3d3095982f6e).

This change enables the setting, and does some minimal work to
configure the system to have it enabled.  This is analgous to what is
done in other deployment mechanisms such as packstack and fuel, and
also what is suggested in the documentation.

Change-Id: Ia508c552d806363f6633d0bcd357c05bf956279f
'}, {'created': '2015-06-05 01:53:00.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure netfilter enabled for bridges with OVS Hybrid

commit_message:
Ensure netfilter enabled for bridges with OVS Hybrid

The OVS Hybrid driver implements security groups by using netfilter on
an intermediate Linux bridge.  Unfortunately distributions differ on
the default status of this (Ubuntu has it on, Red Hat off, at least).

Neutron is unwilling to set this up itself
(If2d316eb8c422dc1e4f34b17a50b93dd72993a99) but I have a review out to
detect this situation and halt the agent
(I8b49298d27a75a864c0066896cbd3d3095982f6e).

This change enables the setting, and does some minimal work to
configure the system to have it enabled.  This is analgous to what is
done in other deployment mechanisms such as packstack and fuel, and
also what is suggested in the documentation.

Change-Id: Ia508c552d806363f6633d0bcd357c05bf956279f

Add non-voting check py34 job to Sahara

We're near to the point when Sahara will work ok on py34, need to
have non-voting job to ensure it's completed and then enable as
voting and add gate job as well.

commit_message:
Add Neutron Loadbalancer v1 create and delete pools

Enable benchmarking of the Neutron LoadBalancer v1
lb-pool-create and lb-pool-delete APIs. Due to the
different API scheme and confusing naming conventions
in Neutron (LB is v1 API and LBaaS for v2 API) the
appropriate code is explicitly marked with 'v1'
since this only implements the API v1 benchmarking.

Change-Id: I83acf4971689f07aab8af5ed6b01d59777529e2e

[{'created': '2015-06-11 15:55:54.000000000', 'message': "Add a non-voting py34 check job to Swift

I was asked to add the Python 3.4 check job to Swift even if tests
doesn't pass right now on Python 3.4. It was decided during Swift
meeting of the 2015-06-10:
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/swift/2015/swift.2015-06-10-21.00.html

Only add the check job to the master branch, ignore Kilo branches and
older since they will not get Python 3 support.

Change-Id: Ib33138be0c6351c882543252a914fd2508247372
"}]
commit_message:
Add a non-voting py34 check job to Swift

I was asked to add the Python 3.4 check job to Swift even if tests
doesn't pass right now on Python 3.4. It was decided during Swift
meeting of the 2015-06-10:
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/swift/2015/swift.2015-06-10-21.00.html

Only add the check job to the master branch, ignore Kilo branches and
older since they will not get Python 3 support.

Change-Id: Ib33138be0c6351c882543252a914fd2508247372

commit_message:
Convergence: move temp_update_requires functionality to tests

During intial stages of convergence to simulate the entire cycle
some part of worker code was written in stack.py.
Now that the convergence worker is implemented, this code needs to
be executed only in tests.

Moved it to proper location.

Change-Id: I52f1611d34def3474acba0e5eee054e11c5fc5ad

in ilo.rst file.

commit_message:
Fixes a bug on the iLO driver tutorial

There is a wrong command on the iLO Ironic driver tutorial page.
The command is in the "Registering Proliant node in Ironic" session
(http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/drivers/ilo.html#id31),
it is used to create a Ironic node that should use the iLO driver,
so there are some parameters to be passed in the command.
The problem is the lack of the "-i" argument just before the
"ilo_address" and "deploy_ramdisk" parameters. The solution is to add
the "-i" argument just before the "ilo_address" and "deploy_ramdisk"
keys.

By following a tutorial, the reader often copy the commands and small
pieces of code that are provided by the tutorial itself, in doing so,
when the copied part has a problem the error just delaying and sometimes
difficult to understand the process causing a waste of time on debugging
the problems that should not exist.

This patch solves the problem by adding the "-i" argument on the command
in ilo.rst file.

Closes-Bug: #1465910

Change-Id: I6cd24b68deacbb9da022a4e34ae607b5c9c950a4

[{'created': '2015-06-17 12:02:56.000000000', 'message': 'Hyper-V: Fix serial port issue on Windows Threshold

On Windows Threshold, a new WMI class was introduced, targeting
VM serial ports.

For this reason, attempting to retrieve serial port connections
fails on Windows Threshold.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an extra check and using the
right WMI class in order to retrieve VM serial ports.

Closes-Bug: #1466056

Change-Id: Ibaf6ac2e77b6324538c6f3dbaacab2a5f065b4ce
'}]
commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fix serial port issue on Windows Threshold

On Windows Threshold, a new WMI class was introduced, targeting
VM serial ports.

For this reason, attempting to retrieve serial port connections
fails on Windows Threshold.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an extra check and using the
right WMI class in order to retrieve VM serial ports.

Closes-Bug: #1466056

Change-Id: Ibaf6ac2e77b6324538c6f3dbaacab2a5f065b4ce

Disable user before deleting

The keystone team suggests disabling resources before deleting to spread
out the cost and to mitigate risk of failure.

commit_message:
Remove raise Timeout::Error from ntp_available

THIS COMMIT IS identical to Ibf2ebb80c04e4314f01b9a45e6a2169e1cde7fbf
it was created to override -1 workflow as we need to merge stuff
for 6.1 RC3

The ntp_available function should not raise a Timeout::Error here as
it should just return false so that the next server should be checked.
This update addresses the case where a Timeout::Error is being raised
rather than having all servers checked before erroring with a
Puppet::Error if no servers answer.

Change-Id: Ide224a0e5dffca6b3dcb8c5e12b732870d07b988
Closes-Bug: 1465598

commit_message:
Add possibility to set dhcp options with enabled q-l3 service

Currently, it's not possible to change values of Neutron's
dhcp options: enable_isolated_metadata and enable_metadata_network
if q-l3 service is enabled, but user should be able to do this.

Change-Id: I95efa39b4b14a0bf567964f007b25b97f1124e7b
Closes-Bug: #1463020

commit_message:
remove hack for nova bug

nova had a bug - it didn't delete root volume of EBS instance.
Now nova can do it so we don't need to cleanup volumes.

Change-Id: I0ed961716b2bc1924d65a20846a7fe3f6fc6c367

commit_message:
Refactor pip check/install & add dependency for CentOS

Use easy_install to install pip to avoid additional dependencies
on CentOS. Refactor the check for an installed pip since it will
now be the same in both OS families.

env-setup.sh was missing a package required if the user is
starting from a very basic CentOS install.

Also fix a minor typo in the script.

Change-Id: I1ee783862b2bc5ad8b5df442ed7ca25732d8f706

Add rally.common.plugin.discover module

Move all related to plugins from utils to discover module
and fix the code and tests to make it work

commit_message:
Dual Scoped Token

This is the new away to provide a token for a project with the is_domain
feature enabled.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte Sousa <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Henrique Truta <henrique@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

bp dual-scoped-token

Change-Id: I03f9b01f0088cfd0b670a4e8b36e01f2c16739c1

commit_message:
Add action type 'run_tasks' for patching tests

For some product patches (e.g. fix in service configuration)
it's necessary to run deployment tasks on slaves after
updating fixed packages. Adding new action type 'run_task'
for that.

Change-Id: I7476e7d4d40cba54b2e12176f6584acdb56b4b95
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Add action type 'run_tasks' for patching tests

For some product patches (e.g. fix in service configuration)
it's necessary to run deployment tasks on slaves after
updating fixed packages. Adding new action type 'run_task'
for that.

Change-Id: I7476e7d4d40cba54b2e12176f6584acdb56b4b95
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

 Closes-Bug:#1455099

(cherry picked from commit 2a91007bfb0058a113cc1733360944cffba5987d)
"}]
commit_message:
Set value for 'pool_maxsize' in keystone

 Set  new parameter 'pool_maxsize' for memcache.
 Default value was set to 100 to fix an issue with
 getting token from keystone after 10 sec timeout.

 Closes-Bug:#1455099

Change-Id: I0dd9b572d3b78c3d30cbfb4e000a457fd69d5e3a
(cherry picked from commit 2a91007bfb0058a113cc1733360944cffba5987d)

commit_message:
Refactor _update_subnet_allocation_pools

Moved _update_subnet_allocation_pools to ipam_backend_mixin.py.
Call _rebuild_availability_ranges with self to make it overridable
on upper level (from non-pluggable backend).

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: If7b1e720f88a2f0177b6772a015ae216f19ee22d

commit_message:
api: record severity change in alarm history

A useless change was done on the original alarm object when
we update the alarm. That have the side effect to hide the change
from the history.

This change fixes that

Change-Id: I9b3030dacf0da83bc0570ed4a6f9d460f178e2be
Closes-bug: #1452264
(cherry picked from commit ecd4ee6566bf718489e85026d26f12ada1d62929)

commit_message:
Backported tempest roles from Master

Change to backport the tempest roles from master into juno. This
change is being done because the deps within Juno no longer allow
tempest to be installed along side OpenStack without a lot of
tom foolery which is not worth the maintenance costs. The upstream
process for installing tempest work and will work with future
versions of the Juno development branch.

Change-Id: I18a690c614253d6b7e2e52e40bf1f14dd6dad87c
Closes-Bug: #1466010

[{'created': '2015-06-16 14:33:51.000000000', 'message': 'Remove raise Timeout::Error from ntp_available

The ntp_available function should not raise a Timeout::Error here as
it should just return false so that the next server should be checked.
This update addresses the case where a Timeout::Error is being raised
rather than having all servers checked before erroring with a
Puppet::Error if no servers answer.

Closes-Bug: 1465598
'}]
commit_message:
Remove raise Timeout::Error from ntp_available

The ntp_available function should not raise a Timeout::Error here as
it should just return false so that the next server should be checked.
This update addresses the case where a Timeout::Error is being raised
rather than having all servers checked before erroring with a
Puppet::Error if no servers answer.

Change-Id: Ibf2ebb80c04e4314f01b9a45e6a2169e1cde7fbf
Closes-Bug: 1465598

code: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/135492/'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-11-19 04:56:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Angus,

I have looked at your patch, and I feel that the external resource support is same as resource level adopt & abandon support, which is defined as part of my blueprint https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124707/. 

so shall we combine these blueprints into one blueprint to provide resource adoption & abandon at REST API, CLI and temaplate levels.

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-11-24 12:07:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Kanagaraj,

We spoke about this at summit and people felt that this was different enough to be a separate thing. Although I am really not big into red tape - I just don't care if the spec is done as one or two. I think they use a similar mechanism, but the behaviour is a bit different that's why people wanted this to be called "external_reference" and not "adopt_data" (which is what i started with). The difference is once the resource data is written we don't allow updates to properties and assume RETAIN in the delete - so it's not really an adopt.

-Angus'}, {'account_id': 10787, 'date': '2014-11-25 11:48:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Can't we do that with adapt resource with some flag "read-only" or "safe-mode" or whatever? With "read-only" option we could apply that to rest of resources (just turn on read-only) and it will mean that no property besides explicitly owned by heat (whatever that means, tbd) won't be touched, also RETAIN on delete will be default? This policy might be useful for any resource, and then adapt will fulfill this use case. Does that make any sense?:)'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-11-25 18:05:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Michael, something similar was discussed at summit and the consensus was that with the state of adopt right now and the uncertainty of its future, have more functionality depend on it was thought unwise. Also, the use case is slightly different than adopt in that adopt says "manage this out-of-band resource forevermore" while this use case is "know about this thing but never do anything with or to it".'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-12-03 02:15:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

inc0: also the use case here is within the template, not via the api. - have a read of the use cases within the spec.'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2014-12-03 09:03:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I can see the benefit of the second use case (pass the information from external resources), but I'm afraid the explained mechanism piles on the same issues that adopt has.

My suggestion would be to have a new section different from resources, and to remove the ability to really "adopt" the elements in it. That would solve the ability to reference external items.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-12-03 23:46:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

I am *really* do not see the advantage of adding a new template level section. I am kinda getting tied of this argument that since adopt is weak in some areas, we must stop all progress.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-12-04 08:53:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2014-12-04 10:27:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

(2 comments)

The new section would solve the first use case, and be more explicit about it. It doesn't solve the other problem though.

I'm not saying we should stop all progress regarding adopt, but what about fixing the issues in the first place, instead of adding other features on top of it?"}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2014-12-04 14:26:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-12-05 01:03:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(7 comments)

I like where this is going.

I prefer the externals to specified in template rather than via an external API, so the user has a local file which documents which resources are currently external.

Also I think I prefer external specified inline with the resource rather than in a different section so that the external is specified alongside the resource it affects.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-12-05 01:21:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

I like the way this idea fits in with the declarative nature of the templates, but I wish we could get some of the abandon/adopt taste out of it, because that turned out to be a minefield.

Also one obvious use case for this would be to pass a parameter such that if none were supplied you'd get a real resource and if one were supplied you'd get an external reference (imagine creating a new Network or using an existing one). It would be nice to see the mechanics of how to do that spelled out."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-12-17 11:57:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-12-31 01:23:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

thanks for the comments, I'll do some more work on this."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-01-14 21:03:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I don't see mention of the specific use case we have in TripleO. Current users have no way to replace individual servers with grouped servers in the new non-mergepy templates we're writing. As such, their only option would be to do an update removing the server, then another one adding it to the appropriate scaling/resource group.

So I think special care needs to be taken to explicitly state how that can work."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-06-03 04:44:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-06-03 04:45:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Fix enable_snat column migration for Postgres + SQLite

Previously, the column was being added with NOT NULL by default.
This caused an issue when performing a migration in Postgres and
SQLite where the default value was not being set.
Change incorrect used 'default' parameter for usage 'server_default'.

Closes-Bug: 1241577

Change-Id: I10039130042796177d26afdec11d08a5ef0be18c

commit_message:
Configure fencing devices

Adds a class to configure fence devices and a helper function which
helps to select the devices for configuration on appropriate nodes.

Depends on patches outside OpenStack's Gerrit:
https://github.com/redhat-openstack/puppet-pacemaker/pull/50
https://github.com/redhat-openstack/puppet-pacemaker/pull/52

Change-Id: I819fc8c126ec47cd207c59b3dcf92ff699649c5a

commit_message:
Fixes unstopped console log worked after live migration

After a live migration is performed, the console.log file
continues to be open at the source host, as the handler was
never stopped.

Stops console log handler for the instance before live migration
is performed.

Conflicts:
	hyperv/nova/migrationops.py

(cherry picked from commit acb783e3ba99b12cee3f5b40dbcd8b715bf8e404)
Change-Id: I866f2159a06497b30b1b8d6d28d699bf0824940a

commit_message:
replace 'metrics' with 'meters' wherever it makes sense

Replaced 'metrics' with 'meters' in all contexts, excluding the
metric system or  where the term is used as name.

Change-Id: If4c32dfe92c28a2079a485a6aec1d61c7b9999a1

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Ensure DIB_RELEASE is exported for fedora""

This reverts commit 7a4c39694864871494b677de7784fdac018c62c3.

Note this time it sets it to F21, not F22, and gets rid of the
duplicate definition that doesn't get exported.

Change-Id: I240ad25d7a73c379559517a2a8399ae8c098314b

commit_message:
Add possibility to specify few targets for patch

Some patches can be targeted for both master node
and OpenStack environments. So erratum.yaml format
and system tests are modified in order to satisfy
this requirement.

Change-Id: I9035c7d7eb8830f089023054d82061d435f8c6c1
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

and system tests are modified in order to satisfy
this requirement.

commit_message:
Update MongoDB puppet module to support 2.6.x versions

  * Sync MongoDB puppet module with
    https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-mongodb
  * Add ability for mongodb_replset type to use
    credentials for executing MongoDB shell commands:
    - add additional parameters for username, password,
      database name if authentication is enabled
  * Add attempts for executing MongoDB shell commands
  * Add connection check to every replica set member
  * Always configure MongoDB with replica set
    - This will allow to add new MongoDB nodes
      to already deployed environments
  * Always setup authentication, users and databases
  * Remove outdated and unused puppet scripts
  * Remove acceptance tests

  Closes-bug: #1383639
  Partial-bug: #1308990

Change-Id: I368f3638b611d5cd3fe5b0a91fffdd96ddd4861a

commit_message:
[Ceilometer] Add  scenario for events and traits

Add scenarios that cover all events and traits Ceilometer API

All scenarios create new user in keystone to store new Event in Ceilometer.
create_user_and_get_event checks GET /v2/events/<message_id>
create_user_and_list_events checks GET /v2/events
create_user_and_list_event_types checks GET /v2/event_types
create_user_and_list_traits checks
GET /v2/event_types/<event_type>/traits/<trait_name>
create_user_and_list_trait_description checks
GET /v2/event_types/<event_type>/traits

Change-Id: I572730d9f69e3d63b29eeedd03ddc24071ffca3d

commit_message:
Correct Hacking rule code

The hacking rule error code should be start with 'M', which stands for
Magnum.

PS: Error number begins with M301

Closes-Bug: #1465895
Change-Id: Ie9565c4a700a1bf85eed8c5db87a8c4012f5254b

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I7069663b6d6224cfb58d637e05f1eebb36246530

commit_message:
Add support for selectable granularity

Instead of retrieving datapoints of mixed granularities from
multi-archive entities, the caller now has the option to specify
the required granularity in seconds.

For example to explicitly select per-minute means:

  GET /v1/entity/UUID/measures?aggregation=mean&granularity=60S

If there is no archive of that granularity defined for the entity,
then the storage driver is free to return an empty response, or to
downsample to the requested granularity on-demand (in the case where
the driver has retained sufficient finer-grained data to do so).

@cdent: well we don't generally pollute the READMEs of openstack projects with installation instructions for standalone external dependencies such as mysql, postgresql, mongodb, rabbitmq, swift etc.

For a variety of reason, including the fact that such instructions:

 * tend to change over time, so would impose a needless maintenance burden
 * tend to be distro-specific, while the READMEs are intended to be distro-agnostic if possible
 * would be mostly unnecessary in any case

So TBH I'd prefer not to break that pattern, especially since installation of InfluxDB is so trivial. On Fedora20 all you need is:

  # wget http://s3.amazonaws.com/influxdb/influxdb-latest-1.x86_64.rpm
  # rpm -ivh influxdb-latest-1.x86_64.rpm
  # service influxdb start

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-06-29 17:10:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

It's not a matter of installing the software requirements.

In a case like this where there aren't specific tests related to this implementation there ought to be some information that says "hey, here's how you can twiddle this stuff to demonstrate that it is useful (compared to some other implementation)". Or if it is an alternate to some established thing it ought to describe a way in which this different thing demonstrates its superiority.

It's an unfortunate side effect of the review process that the artifacts we are creating here are directed primarily to the end point and include little about the learning and exploring process of the developer. I'd argue that validating that learning and exploring is just as important as evaluating the code artifacts. Especially as it would include, for free, getting everybody smarter.

Anyway, in this specific case what it would be useful to know is a sample query or set of activities which demonstrate that the use of influxdb is just as good or better than the pandas+swift setup.'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2014-06-29 17:33:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Hi Chris,

What Julien and Eoghan is trying to do here is the proof of concept implementation first, to see the whole idea is working with multiple backends as options. So no offence, but if you would like to see a cookbook, then feel free to create one, as that would be a help for others too, just how you explained it.

We need more hands for development and also for testing, so if you start play with the currently existing code base and write down your experiences with it, that could be a good starting point for how to test it manually, IMHO. And that which combo is better (I mean swift+pandas or influxdb), I guess noone of us knows in the current phase, so also any reports based on some hands on experience would be really appreciated.

Best Regards,

@cdent: please note that the purpose of this patch is explicitly not to "demonstrate its superiority".

Rather the purpose is, as clearly stated in the commit message, simply to:

* help smoke out impedences between the gnocchi and influx models
* have some simple working code in place to help us hit the ground running with further hacking at the mid-cycle

In any case, in response to your request for guidance on how to "twiddle this stuff to demonstrate that it is useful" I've provided some further simple examples in the README of using curl to submit a bunch of datapoints, retrieve their mean, and finally delete the entity.

Does this help? If not, can you be more specific as to what exactly you need here?

Fair point about the lack of unit tests, but after all this is clearly intended as just a strawman. If we do decide to support InfluxDB as an additional storage driver, then obviously full test coverage will follow.

In terms of your ideas about patch proposals including a log of the author's learning and exploring. While I agree that such activities are crucially important, I don't think it would be practical to require that these learnings be documented as part of the patch proposal process. It is simply not part of our culture to turn the review into a forensic examination of the path traveled by the developer to the point of producing the patch. Rather it is all about the correctness and appropriateness of the patch *itself*.

While such information is valuable if it happens to fall out naturally during the review (e.g. "how come you took approach X instead of Y? ... well, I tried X first, but it turned out not to work for this interesting reason" etc.) then all's the better. But I don't think we can impose the burden of *requiring* that patch authors offer a detailed log of their learnings for validation by reviewers.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-29 20:38:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-06-28 15:10:51.000000000', 'message': '[strawman] gnocchi storage driver for InfluxDB

This is intended just as a strawman to smoke out impedences
between the gnocchi and influx models.

Having some basic working code in advance of the mid-cycle
should help us hit the ground running with further hacking
while in Paris.

The driver has the following attributes:

 * archive (granularity, retention) pairs are stored in
   psuedo-timeseries called <entity_id>-archive

 * entity data are stored in true timeseries called
   <entity_id>-data

 * granularities coarser than 1s are aggregated by mean

 * retention by datapoint count is not currently honored

 * timestamp granularity is limited to 1s, i.e. millisecond
   precision is discarded.

 * related timeseries queries for multi-archive entities are
   not currently batched

Change-Id: I929e5c978ce6af778e70e3600f1d2e3073b32570

commit_message:
gnocchi storage driver for InfluxDB

This is intended just as a strawman to smoke out impedences
between the gnocchi and influx models.

Having some basic working code in advance of the mid-cycle
should help us hit the ground running with further hacking
while in Paris.

The driver has the following attributes:

 * archive (granularity, retention) pairs are stored in
   psuedo-timeseries called <entity_id>-archives

 * entity data are stored in true timeseries called
   <entity_id>-data

 * granularities coarser than 1s are aggregated by mean

 * retention by datapoint count is not currently honored

 * related timeseries queries for multi-archive entities are
   not currently batched

Change-Id: I929e5c978ce6af778e70e3600f1d2e3073b32570

Check alarm periods to the granularities

This patch adds check that evaluation_periods for alarm matches
with granulary of metric(s) that uses for this alarm.

commit_message:
docs: added job to well known tox envlist

This is to make 'tox -l' return the job name in its output (needed to
allow run-docs.sh script in project-config to determine whether the job
is present, to rely on it when generating docs in gate).

Change-Id: I80eb169b7b4e5a3490586722c64394dbb724928d
