subject: [WiP] Add archive policy rules
messages:
[{'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-19 14:42:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-19 14:42:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-01-19 14:45:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't think it's a good path. What I would see is a new object ArchivePolicyRule, which would be composed of 1. a set of rule to apply to matching metrics 2. an ArchivePolicy.

If a metric matches one of the ArchivePolicyRule, then it's applied.

But we want the ArchivePolicyRule to be REST controlled, so it's not going to be in a YAML file."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-19 15:05:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

- gate-gnocchi-tox-py34-postgresql http://logs.openstack.org/71/148271/1/check/gate-gnocchi-tox-py34-postgresql/68a3934/ : FAILURE in 15m 15s'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-19 15:14:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Julien,thanks for the review.  I've used this yaml file as the something ceilometer will use, actually. REST api was needed here, because when we're starting ceilometer collector we probably might have these rules being changed. 

Do you propose the following workflow: let's create archive policies by admin, then let's create archive policy rules via gnocchi REST API (let's say it'll be new table or something managed by indexer)? Issue is that every time we're posting new measures from Ceilometer, we'll need to go to indexer and ask about if current metric is ok with some rule or not - as we'll have no guarantees rules where not changed in gnocchi.

This seems to be kind of slow variant of work - every time we'll be writing measures, we'll need to go to indexer, and I'd love to avoid this on data writing.... Personally to me it looks like setting of these rules seem to be Ceilometer's task - as it has the knowledge about what will be measured - more than gnocchi's task. In my mind the ideal workflow is the following: admin creates archive policies in gnocchi and starts ceilometer with pre-defined rules. Ceilometer updates archive policies in gnocchi to have this information stored in indexer - that'll be useful for data retention in backends like OpenTSDB. These rules can be changed only via Ceilometer's mechanism of config changes - via service restarting like now, or via REST API in future when we'll have persisted storage for configurations and pipelines.

This will allow us to avoid indexer usage in case of measures writing....

What do you think about this?"}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-19 15:27:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Also one idea cam to mind mind - what if I'll as you want (if I got it right) and move all the logic with matching the rules, etc. to gnocchi, and we'll have REST admin-only api for updating the rules. Ceilometer will just post the metrics without any knowledge of what archive policy will be used. Gnocchi itself will go to indexer to find the needed policy due to the rules it has, but it won't be doing this every add_measures request, it'll have kind of in-memory cache with these rules, and will go to indexer only if some_amount_of_time passed from last cache update - this will be checked while measures posting. This will combine all the benefits of logic encapsulation you've proposed with possibility not going to the indexer every add_measures request."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-01-19 16:00:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Rules are applied when metrics are created, not when measures are sent.

If rules are changed after a metric has been created, obviously only newly created metrics will see these rules applied to them.

So the indexer is needed only once when creating a new metric, to fetch the rules, apply them if any, and that's it."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-19 16:06:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

hm, yeah, it looks like it went smh wrong in my mind :)'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-20 17:02:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2015-01-20 17:03:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Remove snapshot.update events as they are not sent

snapshot.update events are not emitted by cinder. So we
dont really need this code until cinder emits this
topic

Change-Id: Ie438642d072237f5c7e1d6741a1cbb2f2b55ddb1
Closes-bug: #1449104

The test was using a setUpClass to initiate datastore
and a datastore version but the same was not deleted
because of which tests are failing.

commit_message:
Fixes the failing tests in mgmt/test_models.py

The test was using a setUpClass to initiate datastore
and a datastore version but the same was not deleted
because of which tests are failing.

Added the tearDownClass to delete the initialized
datastore and datastore version.

Change-Id: I4eeb2d405cd7491a0c13f84d3e5501c46610f855
Closes-Bug: #1464149

commit_message:
Holt-Winters in Custom Aggregation

Added option for holt-winters forecasting in Gnocchi.
Query syntax:

GET /v1/entity/UUID/measures?aggregation=holt-winters&
	alpha=0.1&beta=0.9&granularity=5S

Change-Id: I40c986bf321bfddd64892c377ccc2e61e2bbb263

commit_message:
Move explicit URLs in ironic-install to vars/

To facilitate offline installs, any explicit URLs should be
moved to a location where they can be easily overridden with
a local equivalent.

That way, a default install will use the canonical location, but
a user can easily override this behavior in host_vars/.

(Such gymnastics are not necessary for apt/yum/pip, because those
can be configured to point to local/alternate repositories independently).

** WIP - Needs documentation **

Change-Id: Ic899ed194097f9b88f92b1fbb63f65a941a0186d
Closes-Bug: #1464787

commit_message:
Provide metadata RPCs

This allows q-meta work without falling back to Neutron API.

Note: the use of Neutron API for this purpose is obsolete and
the most environments (including our CIs) do not have it configured.

Fix MNP-144

Change-Id: Iddcfccc16480b72e76a3dbe7d8d3d5fa0ed16ce9

[{'created': '2015-06-16 18:47:59.000000000', 'message': "Use the 'driver_lock' around read operations

To ensure that a file/group/folder is not being
removed while a read is underway (and therefore causing
corrupted msgpack reads) place the driver lock decorator
on the read methods to avoid this rare but possible
occurrence.

Change-Id: Ie2c53bd030aced77282cf575fd1024632e65348f
"}]
commit_message:
Use the 'driver_lock' around read operations

To ensure that a file/group/folder is not being
removed while a read is underway (and therefore causing
corrupted msgpack reads) place the driver lock decorator
on the read methods to avoid this rare but possible
occurrence.

Change-Id: Ie2c53bd030aced77282cf575fd1024632e65348f

commit_message:
Add 2 callbacks to processutils.execute()

Add optional on_execute and on_completion callbacks to allow callers of
procesutils.execute() to track process completion asynchronously.

This could be used to cache the pid of long running tasks associated
with an instance and then clear the cache when the process completes.
While the tasks are running should it be required the pid retrieved and
the process can be signaled.

Co-Authored-By: abhishekkekane <abhishek.kekane@nttdata.com>
Change-Id: Ifc23325eddb523f6449ba06a2deb0885a8a7009d

commit_message:
Use monotonic.monotonic and stopwatches instead of time.time

Monotonic time and oslo.utils stopwatches will not go backwards
and therefore will not cause periodicity + misc. problems where tasks
are ran again or at the wrong times in a system that is having its
clock altered (via ntpd or other).

Related-Bug: #1450438

Change-Id: I90881842185c607eb6c8ea5bb7326a37e1bc3742

commit_message:
Add description param to execution creation API

Now, we can create execution with description parameter using API, for
easily identify the execution.

We can also update the description of execution, but we can not update
state and description at the same time.

Change-Id: I1cf8ca73cdf229b6f3b6584a43cba70db6ac36ab
Implements: blueprint mistral-execution-description

commit_message:
Fix metadata proxy start problem for v6-v4 network

Commit 1b66e11b5d8c0b3de0610ca02c3e10b6f64ae375 introduces
a new problem that metadata proxy will not be started when
an isolated network contains ipv6 subnet with dhcp enabled
and a ipv4 subnet.

This fix separates the checks to enable dhcp and enable metadata
so metadata proxy can be started if there is ipv4 subnet exists
in the network with metadata enabled.

Change-Id: If26806083db225e9ab30d75fa6c728ce99a7cafe
Closes-Bug: 1392564
(cherry picked from commit 4c128c351589ef9f2fc1e084c655a97bdbbda7ce)

commit_message:
Add acceptance criteria and design review to template

Mandatory design reviewers and acceptance criteria
are a must for any spec. Therefore, this patch
adds these additional requirements to the spec template.

commit_message:
Split Midonet Plugin into legacy and new arch

Kilo plugin is compatible with both the legacy ZK-based MidoNet and the
new ZOOM-based MidoNet. Since they differ in the list of features,
split them into two plugins, v1 (legacy) and v2 (ZOOM).

The v1 and v2 plugins are completely separated and only share the
initialization code since v1 is considered to be feature frozen, and
they should evolve independently.

Even though v1 does not really need the pluggable client model, it is
kept this way so that it is easier to integrate with LBaaS service
which uses the same pluggable client model.

Change-Id: I5fda4cb5af2a1097efb3362b2920a64a538e7623
Implementes: MNP-143

commit_message:
Add full-stack test

Currently, the full-stack framework has only one test which only uses
the neutron-server. This patch adds an actual test which makes sure that
once a router is created, an actual namespace is create for it. Since
this test requires 3 processes (neutron-server, l3-agent, ovs-agent),
existing full-stack code is modified to add more streamlined support for
such code.

Partially-Implements: blueprint integration-tests
Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a
(cherry picked from commit 304d68d9741fd15c14263d978e5b0bae43cde58e)

commit_message:
Add rabbitmq max_retries and retry_interval in ironic conf

Oslo.message using rabbit_max_retries and rabbit_retry_interval to
define reconnect rabbitmq server times and interval when can not
connect to rabbitmq server.

Change-Id: I43c682784d5721a09546937b9e587d9e67478883
Partial-Bug: #1439968

commit_message:
Get StringIO from six for Python 3 compatibility

Get StringIO and cStringIO classes and modules from the six module to
make cinder compatible with Python 2 and Python 3.

This patch was generated by the stringio operation of the sixer tool
version 0.4:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ia8a58f83a504f2d2930bf5a0dc2cbaa482c29784

(2 comments)

Some small comment inline, but also:

I think this is a pretty interesting idea but I think it would make more sense for it to be implemented differently:

* Does it make sense for _anything_ that does discovery to be able to use a more generic cache?
* Wouldn't it be cleaner on the caller side if cache expiration was checked inside the cache class when doing the get? same question as Fabio'}, {'account_id': 14118, 'date': '2015-02-10 07:12:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Very good question, below is my understandings:
1. Both "using the cache time interval" and "increasing the polling period" can reduce workload from nova client.
2. The difference is: using cache time interval did not change the period of polling task, just to skip discover instance if cache exists, and call inspector to get metrics for cached vm, then transform and send metrics.
    If we increase the polling period, the metrics getting and sending frequency will get changed which we may not be satisfied.'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-02-11 01:43:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@mizeng, the bulk of the work is the polling aspect rather than the discovery. Also you have no guarantee that no new resources are added you just postpone the discovery period but you may have indeed new resources being created before your cache is expired.
Unless you have a notification mechanism to tell when the cache is invalid I don't see too much value in this proposal..."}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2015-02-11 03:01:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Fabio Giannetti	

this patch is valuable in such scenarios:

in large scale, too many requests to other service api will slow down system performance, with this patch, we can reduce the requests to a low level in not so sensitive or real time required system, 

the interval is 1 minute or less, the cache time is 10 minutes or more, 

if user create a new instance, it will be monitored after 10 minutes or more, but from that time, it can be monitored with interval to 1 minute or less

users lose less but gain more'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-02-11 18:30:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Well, then it really should be handled differently.
What you are describing requires a decoupling of the polling interval vs. the discovery interval.
I am also interested in understanding the overhead of the discovery compared to the actual polling. My understanding is that is minimal.
I suggest to have a spec on something like this that is more valuable and can be applied broadly. My 2c.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-02-11 18:34:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Fabio I don't understand what you really mean by "What you are describing requires a decoupling of the polling interval vs. the discovery interval."

As I understand this change the idea is to continue with the same discovery interval, its just that most discovery requests will be satisfied by the cache.'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-02-11 18:41:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Chris, it seems to me that the value of this patch is to delay the discovery period by an arbitrary amount and keep the polling being the same.
This means that if new endpoints are added the discovery will be delayed for sometime but the data is still collected at the given polling interval.
It seems to me that there is value in saying: I want to discover new resources once a day and poll once a hour. We cannot do this because we have only one polling interval in the sources in the pipeline. If we had a "polling interval" and a "discover interval" we could set them at different rates and solve the problem in a more elegant way than this fake cache.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-02-11 19:29:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Okay that makes more sense Fabio. I agree that is a more elegant way to model the solution.

instance infos. If the instances in nova-compute didn't change, this will be

commit_message:
Add nova cache later for different runs

The currently behavior for compute polling task is to call nova_cli to get all
instance infos. If the instances in nova-compute didn't change, this will be
a waste of time and workload to nova/glance client.

During large deployment, say thousands of compute agents, it will be better to
provide a configurable nova cache layer to save instances information and flush
it periodically, it can dramatically reduce workload from nova/glance client
during large scale deployment. Especially for some scene that don't need high
SLA and allow some delay, it's more useful.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia853c960ed3fbe729c8b83914366b31694c6478d
Implements: blueprint add-nova-cache-layer

[{'created': '2015-06-11 23:42:10.000000000', 'message': "optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there
are many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are
generated and it takes too much time. This issue is due to the
fact that a multipath -ll call against many multipath devices
takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi
devices. This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath
device, however the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll'
call without massive 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by
multipath device:
 1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
    (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by 'multipath -ll'.

commit_message:
optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there
are many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are
generated and it takes too much time. This issue is due to the
fact that a multipath -ll call against many multipath devices
takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi
devices. This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath
device, however the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll'
call without massive 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by
multipath device:
 1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
    (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by 'multipath -ll'.
 2. replace the current nested for loop to identify the IQNs with
    the utility.

(Ported from I77e6eda950726d7ee9a0d92882d4501e70a0d8f8)

Change-Id: I1e5e9eba58a349509e80654ab3058c4ff5d00c0d
Co-Authored-By: Keiichi KII <k-keiichi@bx.jp.nec.com>
Closes-Bug: #1456480

commit_message:
Allow Horizon to access multiple regions

This patch introduces the capability for Horizon to access
multiple regions.

This only takes effect if horizon_available_regions is defined,
otherwise the current default comment is applied to the
local_settings file.

Usage is described via comments in the role defaults and in the
etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml file.

Note that when AVAILABLE_REGIONS is set, OPENSTACK_HOST and
OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_URL are no longer required in local_settings
as per Horizon developer documentation.

Closes-Bug: #1463772
Change-Id: Ia8c0b8be67fd0f479c492d9919b542806f9b204f
(cherry picked from commit a274b2287110e18791e76e77ab71176a225ed315)

commit_message:
Add python-oslo and python-babel as dependencies

These dependencies should be pulled indirectly from the python-neutron
one, but since it seems there are problems installing python-oslo-log, i
think it is much better to specify them explicitily.

Change-Id: I16a791e588780f85236ac166afe3cfdb3eca9c5b
Fixes-bug: https://midonet.atlassian.net/browse/MNP-126

subject: Spec to remove the pipeline from the api server
messages:
[{'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-12-19 15:01:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-19 15:04:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-ceilometer-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/03/143103/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-docs/4b1c172//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 26s
- gate-ceilometer-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/03/143103/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-python27/6822f2a/ : SUCCESS in 1m 30s'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:11:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

How do you envisage how to store the pipeline.yaml in a centralized fashion if not as part of the API service?'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:13:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Fabio this isn't about the storage of the pipeline.yaml. It's about not needing the pipeline in the API. Right now if you post to /v2/meters you can create samples which are then pushed through the pipeline and dispatched to the collector.

The spec proposes that the pipeline not be used, instead notifications are made which are then pushed through the pipeline in the notifications-agent.

What do I need to change to make that more clear in the proposal?"}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:15:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think the issue is that you are stating you are not going to deploy a pipeline.yaml with the API service. I think that is needed since that service is going to be the one to load the pipeline into the database and make it available. Also it will provide the API to make dynamic changes to sources and sinks.'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:16:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

and hey, keep away from my lawn ;-)'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:18:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

just kidding of course (I saw that comments in the IRC chat regarding swift ...)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:33:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My lawn wants less code! :)

Okay, so having a pipeline.yaml available may be necessary to allow for there to be a pipeline-control API. If that comes about, then yes, that makes sense.

However, there's still the fact that the API itself does not need to _use_ the pipeline. That's the main issue that I'm trying to address here. Does that part make sense?"}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:35:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So you are saying that you are going to remove the API part that allows to submit samples from the API, is that right?
This will have impact to the CLI tool too.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:39:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

No, you can still submit samples to the api, but rather than them being published through the pipeline, they will be created as notifications and then the notification agent's pipeline will do any necessary transformations. It says this right in the proposal:

43    +One way to resolve this complexity is to not use the pipeline in the
44	+API server at all. Instead when new samples are posted, format them
45	+as notifications and push them onto the notification bus to be
46	+retreived by the notification agent. The pipeline within that agent
47	+will then do any expected transformations."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:42:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok, got it.
Chris, I think actually the advantage of not having to have all th e scaffolding with queues and so on to post samples it is really good for performance testing.
We have some tools that exploit this and gives us the ability to benchmark the API and storage independently of the limitations that queues may have.
I understand your good intention to make the code less bloated but I think in this case having the ability of testing API performance writes without having to have queues is a good thing.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-12-19 18:15:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You make a good point about wanting to preserve the ability to do performance testing, but there is already a queue involved in the existing pipeline handling: the default publisher in the pipeline is `notifier://` so we already go over the queue in the performance tests that create samples via the API.

Yes, this change would mean going over the queue an additional time, but this is something we frequently do when moving samples from place to place. I think we can gain some real advantages (in making the ceilometer system understandable and improvable) by shrinking the number of places where the pipeline shows up.

Eventually I'd like it to be the case that the pipeline is in only one place (logical not physical, we can easily imagine having many notifications-agents, each processing a pipeline (see https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer-specs/blob/master/specs/kilo/notification-coordiation.rst).

To achieve the kinds of changes the queue will need to be used more and more things will need to create notifications. This is a good thing, not a bad thing: it makes the system far more flexible and far more capable of being distributed."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-01-05 15:51:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

minor -1... i'd just like to have the proposed notification schema and event_type included in spec but i like this proposal."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-01-06 13:34:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Thanks for the review gordc, one response inline, basically begging for your (or anyone's input) because I'm ignorant."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-01-06 14:15:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-01-09 14:46:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

After working with gabbi for a little while (over on I820aa8e8e9442afc0679d881159eafb4b45b4769) I'm starting to wonder if moving the pipeline out of the api server will be too limiting. In that changeset I've create a dispatcher called 'direct' which allows writing directly to the database. This is useful because it minimizes the dependencies during testing. In that changeset I _only_ need to spin up a mongodb, no message bus.

Of course the experience of needing to define a pipeline in that changeset is what inspired this spec. My inner architecture astronaut wants the pipeline to be an entirely separate process, but my get stuff done guy realizes the practical aspects.

meh"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-01-12 17:15:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This change is no longer a priority for me, but after discussion with gordc I'm going to go ahead and leave it open for now in case other people want to think about it.

The reason it is no longer a priority for me is that having the pipeline in the api server means that the testing in 	
I52551f88bc3beac4bf8a92afa45ac70cd97ffcec that is driven by I996cda43609695b7645b9fcf9554d3e928cb92a3 requires no messaging bus, thus limiting the scope of services that are required for the testing."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-11 09:22:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

liusheng will start looking at this. if we can agree upon the implementation , he can start coding it.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-06-11 14:48:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm now pro-this because of the opportunities it provides for the decomposition of the pollsters as well."}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-06-12 08:07:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for Chris's works, I am glad to help if needed :)

BR
liusheng"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-06-12 16:27:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-06-12 16:28:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Spec to remove the pipeline from the api server

As described in the spec, having a pipeline in the api server is a
burden on several dimensions. The spec proposes to replace the
pipeline, used only by a single API resource, with producing
notifications that would be received by the notification-agent,
which would use its own pipeline for transformations.

blueprint api-no-pipeline
Co-Authored-By: liusheng <liusheng@huawei.com>

Change-Id: I099c127eea5d747526800ae69c4abf48ceba92ea

Sorry, probably I'm missing something here. Can you please clarify how this would help understand lifecycle of a resource? As per the last irc discussion on this, I had the impression that we  would have a linked list of statuses where current status points to the last updated status.

Also I would like to see how you would represent a resource status that moves through the following.

PROTOTYPE->SUPPORTED->DEPRECATED"}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-06-17 04:50:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Rabi, I was imagining something like this:

       support.SupportStatus(
            status=support.DEPRECATED,
            version='2015.2',
            previous_status=support.SupportStatus(
                status=support.SUPPORTED,
                version='2015.1',
                previous_status=support.SupportStatus(
                    status=support.UNSUPPORTED,
                    version='2014.2'
                )
            )
        )

And the doc generation will traverse .previous_status to generate the history of the resource."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-17 04:50:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
Retry net deletion on NetworkInUse

To handle race condition where DHCP port deletion is requested after
the network deletion, add a retry logic.

Change-Id: I14ec74013c1c302e366280c7ecd39d6a2473a1ba
Fixes: MNP-130

commit_message:
Add additional arguments to CLI for container-create.

Remove JSON as arguments from container-create CLI.
Add all JSON argument in CLI args like other CLI calls.

Change-Id: I1c23b78ce7f79906344cda54bb4a5ea80d5c7d32
Closes-Bug: #1460907

commit_message:
Add first pass at post_test_hook for functional

Add first pass at getting a post_test_hook working. Once the project
config side of this lands this script can be self gating.

Closes-Bug: #1446442

Change-Id: I562c9d4d45ee4773d80b1ef0ceec6bb9af839a29

commit_message:
Remove deprecated headers in auth_password

According decisions in:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-heat-liberty-deprecation

deprecated headers were deleted, also context class was switched on
using Project header instead of Tenant.

Change-Id: Ibe0b572dd7315a82774077a77579dd1380b59d6d

commit_message:
Add _add_event at the end of update_task

This patch adds call of _add_event method at the end of the update_task.
So now in event-list output user can see, that updating stack is
completed or failed.
Also status reason for update_task were changed to be inline with status
reason in the main stack_task method.

Method set_state is not used due to using stack.store method in the end
of update to avoid duplicate update.

Change-Id: Ic94c95f1558fd67f351696645426c00de8db1bf8
Closes-Bug: #1465321

commit_message:
Pull parsing out of sync_requirements_file.

We're going to be parsing different sorts of files soon, and
sync_requirements shouldn't need to figure that out.

Change-Id: I98677e083cdf55a8626334bee03786aa021045e3

commit_message:
Add windows requirements.

These are existing requireements of Neutron.  They were previously
installed by a build hook.  That caused problems so they were moved to
being specified in setup.py.  Now they need to be moved to
requirements.txt so that setup.py can be kept in sync with the global
version.

Change-Id: I2369971d306c10dc39a1b89698cec95cf7551d07

commit_message:
Remove key 'absolute' from limits client

limits client should be just for getting a resource "limits",
it is not necessary to specify key 'absolute' at all as the library
method.
In addition, this patch removes get_specific_absolute_limit because
the method was just wrapper. That should be implemented on test side.

Change-Id: I5c0ffc136939d0aeb8574c180353715f2a0e2665

commit_message:
Fix incompatiblity issue in VNX manila driver

When running Manila with VNX File OE 8.1.6 or later,
if user creates a NFS share in Manila, driver will
report nas command error when setting nfs permssion.

This fix will use updated nas command to resolve it.

Backport from:https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192122/
Closes-Bug: #1465543

Change-Id: I64ee27858ec796c4c8a23c91883ea6b7e6831ed5

commit_message:
Fix for test_image_create_delete

Add fields missing from CREATE_IMAGE_FORM_FIELDS and are present on actual page.

Reason of test failing is that image creation form of horizon is differ
from the one described in the pageobject. Adding fields to 
CREATE_IMAGE_FORM_FIELDS fixes test.

Closes-Bug: #1464651
Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I6baf6c1918f37cb3b6009919bfbe9615c336a101

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-12 10:35:19.000000000', 'message': 'remove '{{' from variable in loop expression

commit 4bc36f21 introduced a change with the following expression:

with_items: "{{ additional_system_groups }}"

ansible doesn't like this and will complain:

"[WARNING]: It is unnecessary to use '{{' in loops, leave variables in
loop expressions bare"

This commit does as ansible tells us to do

Closes-Bug: #1462572

Change-Id: I852035185b9e6d5480ec6e9e78136cb57307037e
'}]
commit_message:
remove '{{' from variable in loop expression

commit 4bc36f21 introduced a change with the following expression:

with_items: "{{ additional_system_groups }}"

ansible doesn't like this and will complain:

"[WARNING]: It is unnecessary to use '{{' in loops, leave variables in
loop expressions bare"

This commit does as ansible tells us to do

Closes-Bug: #1462572

Change-Id: I852035185b9e6d5480ec6e9e78136cb57307037e

commit_message:
Sync project with nova repo

Differences were introduced due to the fact that
the commit bb8cbb481777d37a81b3a927ad97250a98a5b620 changed
on master after it merged on compute-hyperv.

Solves the differences.

Conflicts:
	hyperv/nova/migrationops.py

(cherry picked from commit 3ffafa0d19dc09bff29dc53ccec4272f26721541)
Change-Id: I9be2a87a3b401edf1161b2824932679c5a940369

commit_message:
Add test case for bay policy check

Two purpose:
Make sure the policy enforce_wsgi decorator is called.
Make sure the request will be disallowed by policy, when it does not
satisfy the policy rule.

Co-Authored-By: yuntongjin <yuntong.jin@intel.com>
Change-Id: I4a4930d7951f416d3553c737c3523c37014d7101
Partial-implements: blueprint policy-enforce

commit_message:
Add hacking rule framework for magnum

This patch adds hacking rule check framework for magnum, and adds first rule:
policy.enforce_wsgi decorator must be the first decorator on a method.

refer this link for why we need this rule.
`https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190140/`

Closes-Bugs: #1465895
Change-Id: If98e47426b391b75755ca0b559aee1baa93b8503

commit_message:
Support multiple marked reqs for the same package

This is needed when a single specifier set is insufficient to handle
both Python2.7 and 3.x. We're not currently dealing with this, but I
have observed it in other projects and we can be forearmed quite
easily.

Change-Id: If1493625d0d2ebf750159ccb8ed0fd22699766a1

commit_message:
service: Adds Windows Oslo Service Workers spec

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.service/+spec/windows-oslo-service-workers

Currently, oslo_service project has a couple of Linux specific
implementations, which makes it impossible to use under Windows.

The goal of this blueprint is implement a way which will allow OpenStack
services to run under Windows.

Change-Id: I4a2833557b99eb637561939bb4619abf9e622bdd
Implements: blueprint windows-oslo-service-workers

commit_message:
Support environment markers in requirements.

This is needed to allow universal wheels when requirements differ
between Python versions (or platforms).

Change-Id: I3a6e88dc3988c9ddf0d4923e5ee6c1aa81e7a4d9

commit_message:
Only update git-review docs on release

Most consumers of git-review only use released versions, so make
sure we update the published documentation for it at release but no
more often than that. Publishing on new commits to the master branch
potentially confuses users since it makes not-yet-released features
look supported.

Change-Id: I20b25d8f0d717c5939538a4c67f86fa9078500bd

commit_message:
Make Python 3.4 voting on git-review again

The Python 3.4 job for git-review has been stable for a while, so
switch it back to voting.

Change-Id: I0f31f725a7929e9239faba191610a3e35e1859c4

commit_message:
Fix spelling of runlevel in init scripts

A number of the init templates in the OpenStack roles have the word
runlevel incorrectly spelt as runlelvl. This commit correct those
spelling mistakes.

Change-Id: I0d1b7d5c5cf088fecf07cf0e1bd676b4e4088e2b
Closes-bug: #1464603

commit_message:
Reduce amount of tempest threads for no-share-servers jobs

Using approach without handling of share servers we have bigger load for
volume creation in Cinder using Generic driver. So, reduce amount of threads
to avoid errors for Cinder volume creations that appear because of lack of
free space.

Change-Id: I738dd9837eb6f951899aef091a6aafe8a4a0945b

commit_message:
Remove support for __version__

The __version__ value was calculated using pbr, which creates a
run-time requirement on pbr. Remove the __version__ property.

Change-Id: I7ea9b4ca3ec78e9c9c2f0094f452923554536868

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Adds multiple security group rules

Until this commit, all security group rules are applied
one by one. This can be problematic in large deployments,
where there are hundreds of rules that need to be applied.

Adding multiple ACLs at once will reduce the processing time
greatly.

Closes-Bug: #1443781

Change-Id: I362f030a95c71b8c86c5fb178493dadc1bc48d4a
(cherry picked from commit e5e96e63acdc1be2b57fcce7b033f874909f80da)

overall this looks like its on the right path. As the goal is to find a place to upstream the PCI tests that intel will be running as part of a 3rd party testing rig.

Note: the alternate home for these tests could be nova functional testing.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-12-04 13:36:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

This doesn't really belong in tempest. The fact that you have to encode the pci info in the tempest.conf is a good example of that fact."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-12-04 14:16:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Why do you say this doesn't belong in tempest ?  IIUC tempest was the place for doing integration testing against the public APIs of Nova. Ultimately this will want to be testing booting of instances using Neutron networks accessed via assigned SR-IOV devices. Since tempest is the place where we do testing of all the different ways to boot guests, it seems like the right place to me."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-12-04 14:35:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

No, Tempest is a test of the OpenStack API in a blackbox context. It's accidental that today it's the only way we test guest booting, not a design point.

We can test this in 2 halves. Test that from API -> libvirt contract we do the right thing, in multiple pci configurations. Then a tool/ in nova that actually ensures that we're creating that mock correctly, that multiple people can run and provide the output (which we can then encode in tree for the tests)."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-04 14:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

It sounds like there are some fundamental design choices that we need to make. I think this warrants a nova-spec. As making the wrong design choices now will lead to pain down the road.'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2014-12-04 23:58:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

tempest also have some testing for scenario, how about put them there? 

we need encode pci information ,just because we need know information to verify the allocation is truly successful. we also could use auto-detection to find some VF to do this(if there is), them eliminating the need of encoded information.

and the nova unit testing hard to cover all path of pci, because now there is no fake devices we could do the allocation verification, it need real hw now.

My concern with this testing is two-fold:

1. It directly couples tempest to the underlying hardware. This is really a layer violation, tempest is not supposed to care about the underlying hardware or implementation details. This really feels like something that nova should be testing internally. I see the point Daniel is making, about being able to verify the whole picture works together. But, that's not what this is actually doing, testing that the PCI configuration is getting setup correctly like this is incorrect. Tempest shouldn't be testing explicitly, that is the realm of nova's testing  to verify that it's creating valid libvirt xml (or whatever else needs to be verified) to boot an instance with the pci passthrough.

If you want to test that nova can bring up a guest and connect to it using SR-IOV and neutron you can use tempest for this, but it would have to be done implicitly. In other words running tempest against a cloud which has this already configured and then running the existing tempest test cases which test connectivity. Looking at the code in this patch it would quite simple to setup (assuming the cloud is already deployed, etc) it would just be a matter of setting up a flavor with extra specs ahead of time and setting that in the tempest.conf. Then you'd be verifying (at least at the top level, which is the domain of tempest) that the pci pass through works for networking. 

2. The policy in tempest is that each new test has to be run in a ci test before it can land. Since these tests require real hardware a 3rd party ci system will be required to vote on this change (and all future tempest changes) to ensure the code added here actually works and continues to work. Until results are posted from such a ci system this couldn't be merged."}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2014-12-12 05:28:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

thanks Matthew Treinish,

for your point 1,  i had setting a bp for moving these tests to the nova.  to testing pci pass-through in the tempest, i got your concern,  we should testing the pci passthrough connectivity or something like that but not this way, thanks point this, it's valuable.

your point 2 means if we need merge test cases to tempest we should setup third CI first( which we currently does), but anteaya told me to running a third party CI and enable it can post comments , we should need firstly  get the cases be merged or reviewed( i might misunderstanding this ,  if i'm wrong fix me, anteaya).  

this is a tie i must resolved. seems there is a way to parallel setting a CI to online and get test cases review merged.   so what process should i following to make the CI online firstly?    we already registed count for that and log server, testing machines etc. 

thanks."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-18 03:04:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2015-06-17 01:14:24.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

seems not suitable for tempest.'}]

commit_message:
pci passthrough basic testcases

these the tests is running by 3rd party CI.for testing
pci passthrough need following steps:
1) config alias for each type devices in nova.
2) in tempest, config pci_resources.resources according
nova pci pass-through alias configration. so tempest know
how to check the allocation is truly success.

[pci_resources]
resources=<aliasname1>:count:vendor_id,product_id;<alias2>...

Change-Id: I30bad99650cb4d37f86bb2fade2338cab7883eff

015-05-11 12:04:52.437 2720 ERROR neutron.plugins.hyperv.agent.security_groups_driver [req-b3fac4e1-5dfe-4b91-b80d-197f05d59d25 None] Hyper-V Exception: HyperVException: WMI job failed with status 10. Error details: The operation failed. - The operation failed.

Failed while applying switch port settings 'Ethernet Switch Port Extended ACL Settings' on switch 'CloudDataTrunk': One or more arguments are invalid (0x80070057). - Error code: 32773 

It started appearing, when 'Stateful' property is being set to True or False on R2."}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2015-05-15 13:28:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hello Sonu.

You mean this commit? https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156354/

I've tested it, it worked fine. There is a tempest test, (testr run tempest.scenario.test_security_groups_basic_ops.TestSecurityGroupsBasicOps.test_cross_tenant_traffic) that tests the security groups and that they behave as expected and they run properly.

Now, the test can't run for Hyper-V, since as default it tests ICMP rules, and Hyper-V cannot add stateful ICMP rules. There is a patch awaiting on gerrit for tempest master, that adds different networking protocols to the test. It is a bit old, but it still works and it worked well for TCP protocol SG rules, for that commit I've linked above, and this one.

Anyways, moving on, the error you received looks very odd to me. It seems that it tried to add a SG Rule (basically, a Msvm_EthernetSwitchPortExtendedAclSettingData object, which has the Caption = "Ethernet Switch Port Extended ACL Settings", the same as in your error) to a switch, which is not possible. Even if you just look at the error, it looks strange... it says: "applying switch port settings on switch".

Also, a couple of things.. what version of neutron / networking_hyperv are you testing? Because I can see the class where the error was logged: neutron.plugins.hyperv.agent.security_groups_driver, which cannot be on Kilo, only Juno or earlier.

What exactly are you trying?'}, {'account_id': 15130, 'date': '2015-05-25 08:45:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Adds multiple security group rules

Until this commit, all security group rules are applied
one by one. This can be problematic in large deployments,
where there are hundreds of rules that need to be applied.

Adding multiple ACLs at once will reduce the processing time
greatly.

Closes-Bug: #1443781

Change-Id: I362f030a95c71b8c86c5fb178493dadc1bc48d4a

commit_message:
Refactors Hyper-V Security Groups

Hyper-V Security Groups logic has become very
convoluted and hard to maintain, mostly due to
differences between Msvm_NetworkAdapterAcl
and Msvm_NetworkAdapterExtendedAcl, used in
Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 and
Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 R2 respectively.

This commit reduces the logic related to security groups
from HyperVUtilsV2, the methods accepting
SecurityGroupRule objects instead, making it easier
to create the rules.

Also, this commit introduces SecurityGroupRuleGenerators,
which will generate the rules, according to the supported
version and many different conditions when creating them.

Change-Id: Ia4ecc1a1ecce19aef000ae39b9efe935ff0db907
(cherry picked from commit 3abcc92f73c17cca8f884ebcf2d767b695e5c9d0)

commit_message:
Refactors Hyper-V Security Groups

Hyper-V Security Groups logic has become very
convoluted and hard to maintain, mostly due to
differences between Msvm_NetworkAdapterAcl
and Msvm_NetworkAdapterExtendedAcl, used in
Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 and
Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 R2 respectively.

This commit reduces the logic related to security groups
from HyperVUtilsV2, the methods accepting
SecurityGroupRule objects instead, making it easier
to create the rules.

Also, this commit introduces SecurityGroupRuleGenerators,
which will generate the rules, according to the supported
version and many different conditions when creating them.

Change-Id: Ia4ecc1a1ecce19aef000ae39b9efe935ff0db907
